Regression Analysis at County level data¶

1. Baseline without controls¶

a. With Total Absolute as Response Variable:¶
Note:¶

Even though Total Absolute does not make sense as concluded from EDA, we are carrying regression on it.

In [6]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

# Assuming 'Grocery Tax' and 'Restaurant Tax' are the features
X = df_diab_total_pivot[['Grocery Tax', 'Restaurant Tax']]
y = df_diab_total_pivot['Total Absolute']

# Add a constant term to the features matrix (required for statsmodels)
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Create and fit the linear regression model using statsmodels
stats_model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

# Print the summary
print(stats_model.summary())

Conclusion:¶

The baseline model with response as total number of diabetics and predictor variables grocery tax and restaurant tax:

  • One percent increase in grocery tax, keeping all other constant, decreases the absolute number by 9.943 x 10^4
  • One percent increase in restaurant tax, keeping all other constant, increases the absolute number by 1.064 x 10^5
  • p-value is close to 0 in both cases. Hence the coefficients of regression are statistically significant
  • Adjusted R-square is 0.016 indicating that the model can explain only 1.6% of variation in total number of diabetics patient
  • Again, this model was fitted only on absolute numbers and we will switch to a more better approach of percentages.

In [10]:
# Checking for multicollinearity
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
vif_data["Variable"] = X.columns
vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]

# Check the VIF values
print(vif_data)

         Variable        VIF
0           const  10.627411
1     Grocery Tax   1.031380
2  Restaurant Tax   1.027672
3      Population   1.016138
Inference:¶

The VIF for predictor variables is small and hence multicollinearity does not exist The VIF with constant variable is high. This can be fixed by scaling if needed.

In [11]:
# Validating for linearity assumptions 

import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import scipy.stats as stats
import numpy as np

# Assuming you have already fitted the linear regression model named 'model'

# Get fitted values and residuals
fitted_values = stats_model.fittedvalues
residuals = stats_model.resid

# 1. Residuals vs. Fitted Values Plot
plt.scatter(fitted_values, residuals)
plt.xlabel('Fitted Values')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Residuals vs. Fitted Values')
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--')  # Add a horizontal line at y=0
plt.show()

# 2. Normal Q-Q Plot
sm.qqplot(residuals, line='s')
plt.title('Normal Q-Q Plot')
plt.show()

# 3. Scale-Location (Spread-Location) Plot
sqrt_standardized_residuals = np.sqrt(np.abs(stats_model.get_influence().resid_studentized_internal))
plt.scatter(fitted_values, sqrt_standardized_residuals)
plt.xlabel('Fitted Values')
plt.ylabel('Square Root of Standardized Residuals')
plt.title('Scale-Location (Spread-Location) Plot')
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--')  # Add a horizontal line at y=0
plt.show()

# 4. Residuals vs. Predictor Plot for ''
plt.scatter(df_diab_total_pivot['Population'], residuals)
plt.xlabel('Population')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Residuals vs. Tax Delta')
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--')  # Add a horizontal line at y=0
plt.show()
Inference:¶

Linearity assumptions are being violated. Lets apply Box-Cox transformations to fix that.

In [12]:
# Applying the Box-Cox transformation

# Apply Box-Cox Transformation to Response Variable
y_transformed, lambda_value = stats.boxcox(y + 1)  # Adding 1 to handle zero values

# Visualize the Transformed Response Variable
plt.hist(y_transformed, bins=20, edgecolor='black')
plt.title('Histogram of Transformed Response Variable')
plt.show()

# Check Lambda Value
print(f'Lambda Value: {lambda_value}')

# Fit a new model using the transformed response variable
stats_model_transformed = sm.OLS(y_transformed, X).fit()

# Print the summary of the transformed model
print(stats_model_transformed.summary())

import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import pandas as pd

df_diab_scaled = df_diab_total_pivot.reset_index(drop=True)
df_diab_scaled

# Extract the independent variables (features) from your DataFrame
X = df_diab_scaled[['Grocery Tax', 'Restaurant Tax', 'Population']]

# Extract the dependent variable from your DataFrame
y = df_diab_scaled['Total Absolute']

# Initialize the StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()

# Fit and transform the independent variables
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Create a new DataFrame with the scaled features
X_scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(X_scaled, columns=X.columns)

# Add a constant term to the independent variables
X_scaled_df = sm.add_constant(X_scaled_df)

# Fit the linear regression model
model = sm.OLS(y, X_scaled_df).fit()

# Display the summary
print(model.summary())

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

# Assuming 'Grocery Tax' and 'Restaurant Tax' are the features

import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import scipy.stats as stats
import numpy as np

# Assuming you have already fitted the linear regression model named 'model'

# Get fitted values and residuals
fitted_values = stats_model.fittedvalues
residuals = stats_model.resid

# 1. Residuals vs. Fitted Values Plot
plt.scatter(fitted_values, residuals)
plt.xlabel('Fitted Values')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Residuals vs. Fitted Values')
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--')  # Add a horizontal line at y=0
plt.show()

# 2. Normal Q-Q Plot
sm.qqplot(residuals, line='s')
plt.title('Normal Q-Q Plot')
plt.show()

# 3. Scale-Location (Spread-Location) Plot
sqrt_standardized_residuals = np.sqrt(np.abs(stats_model.get_influence().resid_studentized_internal))
plt.scatter(fitted_values, sqrt_standardized_residuals)
plt.xlabel('Fitted Values')
plt.ylabel('Square Root of Standardized Residuals')
plt.title('Scale-Location (Spread-Location) Plot')
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--')  # Add a horizontal line at y=0
plt.show()

# 4. Residuals vs. Predictor Plot for ''

plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Residuals vs. Tax Delta')

stats_model_transformed = sm.OLS(y_transformed, X_scaled_df).fit()

# Print the summary of the transformed model
print(stats_model_transformed.summary())

Conclusion:¶

The model with response as number of diabetics and predictor variable tax and population:

  • The lambda value is -0.046. Indicating the new model fit is on (((diabetics number^-0.046)-1)/-0.046). We will call this response as transformed y.
  • One percent increase in scaled grocery tax, keeping all other constant, decreases the transformed y by 0.1036
  • One percent increase in scaled restaurant tax, keeping all other constant, increases the transformed by 0.1053.
  • One unit increase in scaled population, keeping all other constant, increases the transformed y by 0.5187 .
  • All p-value are statistically significant
  • Adjusted R-square is 0.346 indicating that the model can explain only 34.6% of variation in total number of diabetics patient
  • Conditonal large number error has been fixed

Final Conclusion:¶

  • The best model for explaining Diabetics Number variation with Tax, after accounting for necessary controls and corrections of assumptions, is the model with response, (((diabetics number^-0.046)-1)/-0.046); and scaled predictor grocery tax, restaurant tax, population and age control
  • This model explains for 34.6% variability in diabetics number
